      <name>phpMyAdmin &lt; 4.9.5, 5.x &lt; 5.0.2 Multiple SQL Injection Vulnerabilities (PMASA-2020-2, PMASA-2020-3, PMASA-2020-4) - Linux</name>
      <modification_time>2026-01-26T12:26:59Z</modification_time>
      <comment />
      <creation_time>2026-01-26T12:26:59Z</creation_time>
      <host>127.0.0.1<asset asset_id="6ab2bff2-bbe5-4dd3-bff8-c527829efdea" /><hostname>host1.example.com</hostname></host>
      <port>80/tcp</port>
      <nvt oid="1.3.6.1.4.1.25623.1.0.112715">
        <type>nvt</type>
        <name>phpMyAdmin &lt; 4.9.5, 5.x &lt; 5.0.2 Multiple SQL Injection Vulnerabilities (PMASA-2020-2, PMASA-2020-3, PMASA-2020-4) - Linux</name>
        <family>Web application abuses</family>
        <cvss_base>8.0</cvss_base>
        <severities score="8.0">
          <severity type="cvss_base_v3">
            <origin>NVD</origin>
            <date>2020-11-02T21:15:00Z</date>
            <score>8.0</score>
            <value>CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:L/PR:L/UI:R/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:H</value>
          </severity>
        </severities>
        <tags>cvss_base_vector=CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:L/PR:L/UI:R/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:H|summary=phpMyAdmin is prone to multiple SQL injection vulnerabilities.|insight=The following SQL injection vulnerabilities exist:

  - An SQL injection vulnerability was found in how phpMyAdmin retrieves the current username

  - An SQL injection vulnerability has been discovered where certain parameters are not properly
  escaped when generating certain queries for search actions within phpMyAdmin

  - An SQL injection vulnerability was discovered where malicious code could be used to trigger
  an XSS attack through retrieving and displaying results.|affected=phpMyAdmin prior to version 4.9.5 and 5.x prior to 5.0.2.|impact=Successful exploitation would allow an attacker to:

  - create a specially-crafted username and then trick the victim in to performing specific
  actions with that user account (such as editing its privileges)

  - generate specially-crafted database or table names

  - insert specially-crafted data in to certain database tables, which when retrieved
  (for instance, through the Browse tab) can trigger an XSS attack|solution=Update to version 4.9.5, 5.0.2 or later.|vuldetect=Checks if a vulnerable version is present on the target host.|solution_type=VendorFix</tags>
        <solution type="VendorFix">Update to version 4.9.5, 5.0.2 or later.</solution>
        <refs>
          <ref type="cve" id="CVE-2020-10802" />
          <ref type="cve" id="CVE-2020-10803" />
          <ref type="cve" id="CVE-2020-10804" />
          <ref type="url" id="https://www.phpmyadmin.net/security/PMASA-2020-2/" />
          <ref type="url" id="https://www.phpmyadmin.net/security/PMASA-2020-3/" />
